    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "For blueberries, the ideal pH range is quite specific, ideally between 4.5 and 5.5, so aim for that acidic sweet spot. Beyond pH, you'll want to check for levels of macronutrients like Nitrogen (N), Phosphorus (P), and Potassium (K), but also pay close attention to micronutrients like Iron ($\\text{Fe}$) and Manganese ($\\text{Mn}$). If the pH is too high, the soil locks up these essential micronutrients, making them unavailable to the bush even if they are physically present in the dirt. An iron deficiency, for example, often mimics the pattern you initially described!\n\nThis soil testing process will give you a detailed map of your garden's nutritional health. Don't just look at the \"bad\" numbers; the report tells you *why* things are bad, like telling you which specific type of sulfur is needed to lower the pH. Some soils can be heavy clay, which holds onto nutrients tightly, or too sandy, which leaches them away too quickly. It's a whole ecosystem, not just a single measurement!\n\nSo, while pH is the big hurdle, keep an eye on iron and magnesium levels because they are the most likely culprits when acidity",
      "source": "target",
